Array:
- An Array is a container that holds multiple values of the same type(like only number or only characters), arranged in order.
- Think of Array like a row of lockers- all the same size, each holding one item(number).
- In Python, we usually use lists as Arrays, but we also have a special module called Array.

- Basic Array operation - Adding/Changing, Removing/Deleting, Looping, Concatenating, Slicing

#list as an array
arr = ["Haresh", "Sita", "Renu"]
print(arr)

import array #importing array as a module from Python library.
#syntax
#var = array.array('data_type',[data,container])

numbers = array.array('i', [10,20,30,40])
print(numbers)
print(numbers[0])

#adding new value:
numbers.append(50)
print(numbers)

#remove value:
numbers.remove(10)
print(numbers)

#Loop on array:
for num in numbers:
print(num)

#length of the array:
size = len(numbers)
print("Size of araray is ",size)
